<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICATION</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE APPLICANTS MAKES APPLICATION FOR:</BOLD></P>
<P>1. An order declaring that Early Termination Condition #2 (Condition #2) at page 5b of the Tarion Addendum attached to the standard agreement of purchase and sale (the &ldquo;Contract&rdquo; or &ldquo;Contracts&rdquo;), is null and void, or alternatively not enforceable:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI>Condition #2</TI>
<P>Description of the Early Termination Condition: <UNDER>The Purchase Agreement is conditional upon receipt by the Vendor of confirmation that financing for the project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor has been arranged.</UNDER></P>
<P>The Approving Authority (as that term is defined in Schedule A) is: <UNDER>n/a, the determination of the Vendor in its sole, absolute and unfettered discretion, (note the underlining appears in the Contracts).</UNDER></P>
<P>The date by which Condition #2 is to be satisfied is the &ellip10; day of &ellip10;, 20&ellip10;.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>2. An order declaring that by cancelling the Contracts based on Condition #2, the respondents 1945086 Ontario Inc. and 1945087 Ontario Inc. (the &ldquo;Vendors&rdquo;) breached the Contracts because Condition #2 is void and unenforceable.</P>
<P>3. In the event that this Honourable Court grants the relief requested in paragraphs 1 and 2, that there be a trial of an issue to determine whether the respondent Liberty Development Corporation (&ldquo;Liberty&rdquo;) induced the Vendors to breach the Contracts.</P>
<P>4. In the event that this Honourable Court grants the relief requested in paragraphs 1 and 2, that there be a trial of an issue to determine the applicants' damages against the Vendors for breach of contract and against Liberty, in the event that the Court finds that Liberty induced the breach of contract by the Vendors.</P>
<P>5. In the event that the Court grants the relief requested by the applicants in paragraphs 1 and 2, that a Certificate of Pending Litigation be issued as ancillary relief to the declaratory relief to be registered on the property legally described as Lots 1 and 2, Registered Plan 7977, City of Vaughan, Regional Municipality of York in the Province of Ontario, (the &ldquo;Lands&rdquo;) which is owned by the respondent 1834371 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>6. Costs with respect to the relief sought in paragraphs 1 and 2, as against the Vendors and as against those respondents who appear at the application to oppose such relief; and</P>
<P>7. such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THE APPLICATION ARE:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Parties</TI>
<P>8. The applicants, including those listed in Schedule A to this Notice of Application, are purchasers of condominium units in the Cosmos Towers Project. The applicants entered into Contracts with the Vendors for the purchase of condominium units.</P>
<P>9. The respondent Liberty is a real estate development company incorporated under the laws of Ontario, with its head office at 1 Steelcase Road West, Unit 8, Markham, Ontario. Liberty was the developer and promoter of the Cosmos Towers Project. Liberty holds itself out to the public as a leading development manager of residential buildings in the greater Toronto area who is dedicated to total customer care and whose principals have over thirty years of hands-on experience in the development and construction industries. Darvish Fereydoon is a director and the president of Liberty.</P>
<P>10. The respondent 1945086 Ontario Inc. is a corporation incorporated under the laws of Ontario, with its head office at 1 Steelcase Road West, Unit 8, Markham, Ontario. 1945086 Ontario Inc. is one of the two vendors of the condominium units sold to the applicants (a &ldquo;Vendor&rdquo;, or together with the respondent 1945087 Ontario Inc, the &ldquo;Vendors&rdquo;). Darvish Fereydoon is a director and the president of 1945086 Ontario Inc. Michael Durisin is a director and vice-president of 1945086 Ontario Inc. Latif Fazel is a director and secretary of 1945086 Ontario Inc. Joseph Salek is a director and vice-president of 1945086 Ontario Inc. Michael Uster is a director and treasurer of 1945086 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>11. The respondent 1945087 Ontario Inc. is a corporation incorporated under the laws of Ontario, with its head office at 1 Steelcase Road West, Unit 8, Markham, Ontario. 1945087Ontario Inc. was one of the two vendors of the condominium units sold to the applicants (a &ldquo;Vendor&rdquo;, or together with the respondent 1945086 Ontario Inc, the &ldquo;Vendors&rdquo;). Darvish Fereydoon is a director and the president of 1945087 Ontario Inc. Michael Durisin is a director and vice-president of 1945087 Ontario Inc. Latif Fazel is a director and secretary of 1945087 Ontario Inc. Joseph Salek is a director and vice-president of 1945087 Ontario Inc. Michael Uster is a director and treasurer of 1945087 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>12. The respondent 1834371 Ontario Inc. is a corporation incorporated under the laws of Ontario, with its head office at 1 Steelcase Road West, Unit 8, Markham, Ontario. At the time that the Vendors sold condominium units to the applicants, this respondent was the owner in fee simple of the Lands where the condominium towers were to be constructed. 1834371 Ontario Inc. continues to be the owner. Darvish Fereydoon is a director and the president of 1834371 Ontario Inc. Michael Durisin is a director and vice-president of 1834371 Ontario Inc. Latif Fazel is a director and secretary of 1834371 Ontario Inc. Joseph Salek is a director and vice-president of 1834371 Ontario Inc. Michael Uster is a director and treasurer of 1834371 Ontario Inc.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Cosmos Towers Project (Origin and Cancellation)</TI>
<P>13. In or about 2016, Liberty promoted the sale of pre-construction condominium units in three proposed towers for a Liberty project called the Cosmos Condominiums or Cosmos Towers (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;), to be located in Woodbridge, at premises legally described as part of Lots 1 and 2, Registered Plan 7977, City of Vaughan, Regional Municipality of York in the Province of Ontario. The Project was comprised of approximately 1,100 units.</P>
<P>14. The Project quickly sold out, meaning all condominium units available for sale were sold to the applicants and other purchasers, prior to any of the three towers in the Project being constructed.</P>
<P>15. In or around the month of May, 2016 until in or about the month of November,2016,all applicants signed a standard form agreement of purchase and sale (the &ldquo;Contract&rdquo;) with one of the two numbered company Vendors. The Contracts were drafted by the Vendors and contained identical terms and conditions including Condition #2.</P>
<P>16. All applicants provided a deposit and made all requisite installment payments/deposits in accordance with the Contract.</P>
<P>17. In or around April, 2018, (some two years after the applicants had committed to purchasing a unit in the Project and seen the price for condominium units in Vaughan drastically increase), the applicants were notified by Liberty and the Vendors that the Project was cancelled. The Contracts were terminated, ostensibly based on Condition #2.</P>
<P>18. A cancellation letter was mailed to the applicants and all other purchasers. The letter was written on Liberty letterhead, including Liberty's trademark/logo and signed by Shawn Richardson, Director of Sales and Marketing for Liberty, for and on behalf of the Vendors. The letter for and on behalf of 1945086 Ontario Inc. reads:
<QUOTE><P>PLEASE NOTE THAT:</P>
<P>1. The Early Termination Condition #2 contained on page 5B of the Tarion Addendum attached to die Purchase Agreement described as follows:</P>
<P><UNDER><EM>The Purchase Agreement is conditional upon receipt by the Vendor of confirmation that financing for the project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor has been arranged</EM>.</UNDER> <EM>The Approving Authority (as that term is described in Schedule A) is:</EM> <UNDER><EM>n/a, the determination of the Vendor in its sole, absolute and unfettered discretion, (note the underlining appears in the letter)</EM></UNDER></P>
<P>Pursuant to paragraph 6(d) of the Tarion Addendum, the date by which the Early Termination Condition #2 must be satisfied is July 2, 2019, which is 90 days before the First Tentative Occupancy Date.</P>
<P>2. Please take note that Early Termination Condition #2 has not been satisfied nor waived within the required period under the Purchase Agreement despite us having taken all commercially reasonable steps to satisfy same.</P>
<P>3. In accordance with Section 6 and 10(d) of the Tarion Addendum attached thereto, the Purchase Agreement is hereby terminated.</P>
<P>4. Following this notice via a subsequent letter in the next 10 days will be a cheque representing reimbursement of all deposit monies paid by you together with any interest as prescribed by the <UNDER>Condominium Act, 1998</UNDER> to the same Purchaser address herein.</P>
<P>Yours truly, For and on behalf of 1945086 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>Per:</P>
<P>Shawn Richardson, Director of Sales and Marketing</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. In addition to the cancellation letter, Liberty also forwarded a letter to the applicants and all other purchasers. Liberty claimed that the &ldquo;Vendors&rdquo; were forced to cancel all Contracts and that the Vendors would be returning all deposits. The letter was also signed by the same Shawn Richardson, Director of Sales &amp; Marketing for Liberty. This letter read in part:
<QUOTE><P>While the Cosmos project earned strong sales success, support from realtors, and encouragement from key stakeholders, we are advised by the project vendor that at this time financing for the project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor cannot be arranged.</P>
<P>As the financing arrangements on satisfactory terms to the project vendor cannot be obtained it will force the project vendor to now cancel all Agreements of Purchase and Sale in keeping with the terms of these agreements and the Early Termination Conditions in the agreement's Tarion Addendum. As such, the project vendor shall be returning all purchaser deposits collected to date in the days to come. The required Tarion notice effecting same is attached.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>We recognize that today's decision will impact our purchasers and the project vendor would have preferred an alternative to cancelling agreements. Unfortunately there is no alternative. Accordingly, working with the vendor we must move to cancel all agreements, distribute refund of deposits, and work to ensure the process for return of these funds is smooth, efficient and easy for those affected.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>20. As of the date of this Notice of Application, Liberty is planning a new condominium project adjacent to the cancelled Project (being the project cancelled ostensibly for lack of satisfactory financing) and will be redeveloping its recent acquisition of the Promenade Mall to modernize the mall and construct three residential apartment towers of 28 to 35 stories with 1,006 units, as well as offices and a hotel with a combined 24,392 square metres of space.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Condition #2 is prohibited by Tarion.</TI>
<P>21. Each applicant entered into a standard form contract with one of the respondent Vendors to purchase one or more units in the Project The Contract was drafted by the Vendors, including Condition #2.</P>
<P>22. For purchasers of units in Towers A and B, the purchaser entered into the Contract with the respondent 1945086 Ontario Inc. For purchasers of units in Tower HI, the purchasers entered into the Contract with the respondent 1945087 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>23. The Contract provides that the purchaser will make down payments of specified amounts on a specified number of days following the execution of the Contract. Under the heading &ldquo;CLOSING&rdquo;, the Contract provides that the purchase and sale of the condominium unit will be completed and the unit will be transferred to the purchaser &ldquo;in accordance with the terms of this Agreement on a date (the &ldquo;Unit Transfer Date&rdquo;) that is the later of (i) the Occupancy Date and (ii) a date fixed by the Vendor upon which the transfer of the Unit acceptable for registration is delivered to the Purchaser or his solicitor.&rdquo;</P>
<P>24. In each instance, the Contract is signed by both the purchaser(s) and the respondent Vendor.</P>
<P>25. The Contract includes a twelve page Tarion Condominium Form (&ldquo;Tarion Addendum&rdquo;), which by regulation is incorporated into all pre-construction condominium contracts in Ontario and constitutes a form of consumer protection legislation.</P>
<P>26. Tarion Warranty Corporation (&ldquo;Tarion&rdquo;) is a not-for-profit corporation incorporated under the <EM>Corporations Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.38, which is responsible for administering the warranties under the <EM>Ontario New Home Warranties Plan Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c 0.31, for new home buyers including purchasers of condominium units.</P>
<P>27. The Tarion Addendum provides in paragraph 6(b) for certain defined early termination conditions that may be included by the Vendors in the Contract, which are set out in Schedule A to the Tarion Addendum. No early termination condition can be included in the Contract other than the conditions authorized in Schedule A by Tarion.</P>
<P>28. The early termination condition authorized by Tarion is set out in paragraph 1.(b)(ii) of Schedule A and reads as follows:
<QUOTE><P>1. <BOLD>The Vendor of a condominium home is permitted to make the Purchase Agreement conditional as follows:</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>(b) upon:
<QUOTE><P>(ii) receipt by the Vendor of confirmation that financing for the project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor has been arranged by a specified date;</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. The Vendors' version of the permitted early termination condition is set out in an Appendix located at page 5B of the Tarion Addendum, which is reproduced below:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI>Condition #2</TI>
<P>Description of the Early Termination Condition: <UNDER>The Purchase Agreement is conditional upon receipt by the Vendor of confirmation that financing for the project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor has been arranged.</UNDER></P>
<P>The Approving Authority (as that term is defined in Schedule A) is: <UNDER>n/a, the determination of the Vendor in its sole, absolute, and unfettered discretion.</UNDER></P>
<P>The date by which Condition #2 is to be satisfied is the &ellip10; day of &ellip10;, 20 &ellip10;.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>30. Condition #2 was reproduced in the cancellation letter sent to all applicants as the basis for cancelling the Contract, as described in paragraph 18 of this Notice of Application.</P>
<P>31. Condition #2 is not authorized/permitted by Tarion. It does not comply with paragraph 6(a) or 6(b) of the Tarion Addendum. Paragraph 6(a) reads as follows:
<QUOTE><P>(a) The Vendor and Purchaser may include conditions in the Purchase Agreement that, if not satisfied, give rise to early termination of the Purchase Agreement, but only in the limited way described in this section.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. Condition #2 includes &ldquo;the determination of the Vendor in its sole, absolute, and unfettered discretion.&rdquo; The Vendors have therefore included one or more conditions which do not conform with the limited way early termination of the Purchase Agreement is authorized in paragraph 6(a).</P>
<P>33. Paragraph 6(b) reads as follows:
<QUOTE><P>(b) The Vendor is not permitted to include any conditions in the Purchase Agreement other than: the types of Early Termination Conditions listed in Schedule A; and/or the conditions referred to in paragraphs (i), (j) and (k) below. Any other condition included in a Purchase Agreement for the benefit of the Vendor that is not expressly permitted under Schedule A or paragraphs (i), (j), and (k) below is deemed null and void and is not enforceable by the Vendor, but does not affect the validity of the balance of the Purchase Agreement</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>34. The permitted early termination condition, as set out in 1(b)(ii) of Schedule A, is limited to confirmation that financing for the Project on terms satisfactory to the Vendor has been arranged. Condition #2 includes additional terms and conditions, &ldquo;the determination of the Vendor in its sole, absolute, and unfettered discretion.&rdquo; Financing on terms satisfactory to the Vendor is not the same type of condition as Condition #2.</P>
<P>35. Paragraph 6(f) of the Tarion Addendum provides:
<QUOTE><P>(f) The Vendor agrees to take all commercially reasonable steps within its power to satisfy the Early Termination Conditions identified in subparagraph (d) above.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>36. The Tarion Addendum provides for an all-commercially-reasonable-steps standard, which the Vendors must satisfy before exercising and when exercising early termination condition 1(b)(ii). Condition #2 effectively contracts the Vendors out of the commercially reasonable standard, in favour of a sole/absolute/unfettered discretion standard.</P>
<P>37. Pursuant to paragraph 6(b), Condition #2 is therefore deemed null and void and is not enforceable by the Vendors because &ldquo;any other condition included in a purchase agreement for the benefit of the Vendor that is not expressly permitted under Schedule A...is deemed null and void and not enforceable by the Vendor.&rdquo;</P>
<P>38. The Vendors therefore breached the Contracts by terminating the Contracts based on Condition #2.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Damages</TI>
<P>39. The applicants have all sustained damages for breach of contract, including the loss of the market value of the unit at closing compared to the purchase price, or alternatively, the loss of the market value of the unit at the time of the breach, compared to the purchase price; loss of use and enjoyment of the unit once built; loss of their promised home; lost rental income; enhanced carrying charges and the enhanced cost to replace the unit with a comparable alternative condominium unit in Vaughan at today's prices or in some cases the complete loss of the ability to purchase a condominium unit, as current prices have made it unaffordable.</P>
<P>40. The applicants claim that the damages for breach of contract can be determined on an aggregate damages basis.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Liberty induced the Vendors to breach the Contracts</TI>
<P>41. The Contracts between the Vendors and applicants were valid and enforceable contracts.</P>
<P>42. Liberty knew of the Contracts between the applicants and Vendors.</P>
<P>43. Liberty was the developer of the Project and promoted the sale of the condominium units to the applicants and other purchasers.</P>
<P>44. Liberty and the Vendors have always operated as one joint enterprise where Liberty completely controlled the operations of the Vendors in all respects. Liberty made the decision to cancel the Project and made the decision to justify the cancellation based on Condition #2. Liberty then induced and directed its Vendor numbered companies to breach the Contracts.</P>
<P>45. Liberty exercised complete control over the Vendors directly or alternatively did so indirectly, through means of affiliated corporations or family members, and/or through owning or controlling the majority of the common shares in the Vendor corporations.</P>
<P>46. The applicants suffered damages as a result of Liberty inducing a breach of the contracts.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>A certificate of pending litigation is warranted.</TI>
<P>47. 1834371 Ontario Inc. and the Vendors are controlled by Liberty and operated together as one economic unit in making all decisions about the Project, including its cancellation.</P>
<P>48. 1834371 Ontario Inc. formed part of the organization who unlawfully cancelled the Contracts.</P>
<P>49. On or about January 31, 2012, 1834371 Ontario Inc. purchased the Lands municipally described as 2951 Highway #7 West, Vaughan; 180 Maplecrete Road, Vaughan; and 190 Maplecrete Road, Vaughan.</P>
<P>50. On January 26, 2017, a charge was registered against the Lands in the amount of $100 million in favour of The Guarantee Company of North America. It continues to be a charge on title as of the date of pleading. The Chargor is 1834371 Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>51. Schedule 2 of the Charge includes a collateral mortgage dated January 24, 2017, regarding an indemnity agreement between 1945086 Ontario Inc. and 1945087 Ontario Inc., the Chargee and 1834371 Ontario Inc. As of the date of pleading, the applicants do not know the terms of the indemnity agreement.</P>
<P>52. The respondent 1834371 Ontario Inc. knew that the Vendors and Liberty were promoting the Project and knew that the Vendors sold condominium units to the applicants, thereby providing the applicants with an interest or beneficial interest in the Lands.</P>
<P>53. 1834371 Ontario Inc. held the Lands in trust for the Vendors, on the basis that the Lands would be conveyed to a condominium corporation at closing.</P>
<P>54. A certificate of pending litigation issued against the Lands is warranted as the applicants have an equitable interest in the Lands; the Vendors have no assets; 1834371 Ontario Inc. is a third party beneficiary to the Contracts; and 1834371 Ontario Inc. holds the Lands in trust for the Vendors to complete the Contracts. Liberty deliberately arranged for a corporation, which it completely controls, to hold title to the Lands knowing that if the Vendors breached the contracts, the Vendors are shell corporations without assets. Therefore, in the circumstances, the justice of the case is such that this Court should disregard the separate corporate existence of 1834371 Ontario Inc. for the purposes of issuing a certificate of pending litigation.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The applicants may bring this proceeding as an application under rule 14.05 of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</TI>
<P>55. The applicants can bring this proceeding as an application because the applicants are seeking a determination of the applicants' rights that depend on the interpretation of a contract and/or the interpretation of a statute, being the <EM>Ontario New Home Warranties Plan Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c 0.31 and regulations thereunder, pursuant to Rule 14.05(3)(d) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>56. The applicants can further bring this proceeding as an application because:
<P1>a. the applicants are seeking a declaration that the respondent Vendors breached the contract, pursuant to Rule 14.05(3)(g) of the <EM>Rules</EM>;</P1>
<P1>b. with respect to the claim for breach of contract against the Vendors, there are not likely to be any material facts in dispute, pursuant to Rule 14.05(3)(h) of the <EM>Rules;</EM> and</P1>
<P1>c. the applicants seek as ancillary relief to the declaration a certificate of pending litigation, pursuant to Rule 14.05(3)(g) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The applicants and respondents are proper parties to the Application.</TI>
<P>57. All the applicants may join their claims against the respondents in one application, pursuant to rule 5.01(1) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194 (&ldquo;<EM>Rules</EM>&rdquo;)</P>
<P>58. The applicants can bring different claims against the respondents in the same application, and it is not necessary for each of the applicants to have an interest in all of the relief claimed or in each of the claims against the respondents, pursuant to rule 5.01(2) and (3) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>59. The applicants may join each of their claims against the respondents in this Application because they are asserting claims that arise out of the same transaction or occurrence or series of transactions or occurrences; there are common questions of law or fact; and joining the claims in the same application will promote the convenient administration of justice, pursuant to rule 5.02(1) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>60. Liberty is a proper party to the Application pursuant to rule 5.03(1) of the <EM>Rules</EM> because it has an interest in participating in the Application to determine the declaratory relief sought in paragraphs 1 and 2. In the event that the relief is granted, the applicants seek a trial of an issue against Liberty.</P>
<P>61. The applicants may join their claims against all the respondents including Liberty in this Application because they are asserting claims against the respondents which arise out of the same transaction or occurrence, or series of transactions or occurrences; there are common questions of law or fact; damage or loss has been caused to the applicants by more than one of the respondents including by Liberty and there is doubt as to the respondents whom the applicants are entitled to relief or the respective amounts for which each respondent may be liable; and joining the claims in the same Application will promote the convenient administration of justice, pursuant to Rule 5.02(2) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>62. The respondent 1834371 Ontario Inc., as owner of the Lands, is a proper party to the Application because the applicants seek a certificate of pending litigation pursuant to Rule 42 of the <EM>Rules</EM> and section 103 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43, in the event that the declaratory relief is granted.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The applicants seek to have the issue of whether the Vendors breached the Contracts determined on this Application with the remaining issues ordered to proceed to a trial of an issue.</TI>
<P>63. The applicants are seeking on this Application a declaration that Early Termination Condition #2 (on which the Vendors solely relied to terminate the Contract) is null and void and not enforceable, and therefore the Vendors breached the Contract in terminating the Contract.</P>
<P>64. In the event that the Court finds that the respondent Vendors breached the Contracts and grants declaratory relief, the applicants then seek to have the cause of action against Liberty for inducing breach of contract and the applicants' damages against the Vendors and Liberty proceed to a trial of an issue, pursuant to Rules 1.05, 38.10(1)(b) and 38.10(3) of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>65. Determining the interpretation of the Contract and consequent question of whether the Vendors breached the Contract by cancelling the Project, is the central issue in these proceedings. The application is therefore the most proportionate, expeditious, and least expensive means of determining the merits of this proceeding, pursuant to Rule 1.04 of the <EM>Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>66. The <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, Reg. 194, as amended, including Rules 1.04, 1.05, 5.01, 5.02, 5.03, 13.1.02, 14.05, and 38.</P>
<P>67. The <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43, includes section 103.</P>
<P>68. The <EM>Ontario New Home Warranties Plan Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c O.31, and,</P>
